{
  "doc_id": "51620",
  "text": "Fbln5 is a member of the fibulin family of proteins and consists of six calcium-binding epidermal growth factor-like repeats, one of which contains an integrin-binding RGD motif and a COOHterminal fibulin-type module [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Fbln5 is crucial for proper assembly of elastic fibers as it tethers tropoelastin to microfibrils where it is crosslinked by lysyl oxidase to form mature elastic fibers (Liu et al., 2004; [CITATION_3] . Mice that are deficient in Fbln5 have fragmented and disorganized elastic fibers leading to loose skin, vascular anomalies and alveolar defects [CITATION_4] . Fbln5 protein is secreted into the ECM by fibroblasts, vascular smooth muscle cells (VSMCs) and endothelial cells, and associates with cells through integrins a V b 3 , a 4 b 1 and a 5 b 1 (Lomas et al., 2007; [CITATION_5] . Recent studies have suggested that Fbln5 can regulate angiogenesis. In vitro experiments showed that Fbln5 antagonized vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF) signaling thereby abrogating VEGF-induced proliferation and migration of endothelial cells (Albig et al., 2006; Albig and Schiemann, 2004) . In addition, in vivo studies indicated an increase in vascular invasion into polyvinyl sponges that were implanted into Fbln5 -/-mice compared with wild-type (WT) animals [CITATION_6] . The exact mechanism by which Fbln5 exerts its effect on angiogenesis is unknown. Given these results and the aberrant vessel formation in Fbln5-null animals, we sought to determine whether tumor growth is altered in Fbln5 -/-mice owing to effects on angiogenesis. ",
